  "prompt": "Why are liquids not allowed on flights?",
  "response": "Liquids are allowed on flights, but there are restrictions on the amount and type of liquids that can be carried in carry-on luggage. These restrictions were put in place by the Transportation Security Administration (TSA) in the United States and similar agencies in other countries after a foiled terrorist plot in 2006 that planned to use liquid explosives to blow up airplanes.\n\nThe current regulations state that passengers are allowed to carry liquids, gels, and aerosols in containers of 3.4 ounces (100 milliliters) or less, and all containers must fit in a single, clear, quart-sized, zip-top plastic bag. Each passenger is allowed one bag.\n\nThere are some exceptions to these rules, such as medications, baby formula, and breast milk, which are allowed in larger quantities but may require additional screening.\n\nLiquids in checked baggage are not subject to the same restrictions, but they should be packed in leak-proof containers and placed in a plastic bag to prevent damage to other items in the suitcase.\n\nIn summary, liquids are allowed on flights, but the amount and type of liquids that can be carried in carry-on luggage are restricted for security reasons.",
